
To use the new guild soul inherit, you'll of course need to #include <mudlib.h>
The #define for the guild soul inherit is, predictably enough, GUILD_SOUL
Note that GUILD_SOUL inherits nothing else, so it can be used in multiple
inheritance situations with anything on the OBJECT tree (and usually will be).

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The following functions should be called from reset() of the guild_soul:

void set_guild(string sName)
  This function sets the name of the guild, which must be registered with the
  Guild Daemon. Proper captalization is necessary.
  
  Example: set_guild("Paladin");

void set_main_channel(string sChannel) 
  This function tells the guild soul what the name of the main channel is
  which ALL guild members receive. This channel must be a real, static
  channel registered in the USER_D, and is usually simply the name of the
  guild rendered to lower case.
  
  Example: set_main_channel("paladin");

void set_guild_path(string sPath  OR   string *  asPaths) 
  This function tells the guild soul what command paths (/cmds/..) the 
  guild deals with. A single string or an array of strings can be
  passed to this function, and the function can be called several times
  to add additional paths if the single-string format is preferred.
  
  Example: set_guild_path("/cmds/guilds/paladin");
           set_guild_path(({"/cmds/guilds/ranger",
               "/cmds/guilds/ranger/emotes"}));

void add_extra_channel(string sChannel, string sDescription, string sColor)
  This function tells the guild soul to create a dynamic channel for use by
  this guild, with the given name, description, and color. Whether or not
  a specific player is added to the channel or not is controlled by
  overloading can_join_channel(). See the section on overloads.
  
  Example: add_extra_channel("mitra","Followers of Mitra discussion","|MK0");
           add_extra_channel("lord","Lord Paladin Discussion","|GKB");

** Note for those unfamiliar with multiple inheritance in LPC. It is necessary
    to call BOTH reset() functions in the parent inherits explicitly by use
    of the scope resolution operator. A similar process must be followed for
    init().
    
  Example:   armour::reset(arg);
             guild_soul::reset(arg);

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The following functions exist in the guild soul inherit but should be
  overloaded in any individual guild soul. Failure to overload these properly
  will usually result in generic defaults.

string query_msg_in()
string query_msg_out()
string query_mmsg_in()
string query_mmsg_out()
  These should return the relavent msg to be applied to members of this guild.
   
   Example: string query_msg_in() { return "$N enters proudly from the $D."; }
            string query_mmsg_in() { return "$N appears out of nowhere."; }

string query_guild_header()
  This should return the header used to mark messages on the main guild
    channel.
    
  Example: string query_guild_header() { return "[PALADIN]"; }

string query_death_message() 
string query_death_general() 
  These functions should return the message to be broadcast on the main guild
    channel when an individual in the guild dies. $N represents the name of
    the person killed, and $T represents the living object that killed him.
    Note that use of $T in query_death_general() is not allowed.
    
    Example: string query_death_message() {
       return query_guild_header() + " Mitra's Paladin $N falls to $T."; }

string query_login_message()
string query_logout_message() 
  These functions should return the message to be broadcast on the main
    guild channel when a non-applicant individual in the guild logs in or
    out. Note that most guild souls should already support this.
   
   Example: string query_login_message() { 
     return "\<>Mitra smiles as " + CAP(REAL) + " enters Darkwind. <>"; }

int can_join_channel(string sChannelName) 
  This function controls whether or not a player may join a guild's dynamic
    channel (see add_extra_channel() for how to create such channels).
    This function is called for every dynamic channel in the guild and
    a return result of 1 indicates that the channel will be added, 
    while a return of 0 indicates that the channel should be skipped.
    Since this is done AFTER reloading/move of the guild soul to the
    player, it may refer to individual player data.

  Example:
    int can_join_channel(string sChannelName) {
      if(sChannelName == "mitra") return 1;
      return (GLEVEL == 15);
    }

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Other function information

void save_soul()
  This function causes the soul data to be saved, if the possessor is a PC.

void set_default_variables() 
  This function is called when a player enters a guild for the first time
  (or otherwise lacks a savefile for the guild). It can be overloaded to
  set up defaults for guild-specific variables. If so, be sure to call
  the inherited version.

void set_timer(int iNumSeconds, string sTimerName) 
  This function sets an individual or group timer that is stored and
    checked independently of the general power timer.

status check_timer(string sType)
  This function checks an individual or group timer. Return value is
  0 if the timer is set and not expired (i.e. attempts to use this
  category should fail), 1 otherwise.

status query_timer(string sType) 
  This function returns the time at which an individual or group
  timer expires.
  
To include guild-specific code in the setup and guild removal functions,
  overload void init() and status remove_guild(int iSilently)
  respectively. Remember to call the inherited version!
  Do not use init_arg() - monsters do not get init_arg() called when
  guild souls are created for them!
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Notes on converting existing guild souls:

The following code should be removed and/or replaced with standard inherit
   calls:
   
Death messages
Login/out messages
Changes to msgin/out
Setting/removal of command paths
Adding/removal of channels
Creation of dynamic channels
Setting of attributes on the player
Incorrect calls to save
Add_actions that force guild soul to save
Code that restores the soul from a savefile
Code that backs up the guild savefile

Basically, all that should be left in individual guild souls is information
  that is specific to that guild only, and functions to carry out tasks
  specific to that guild only.
